<paragraph blockId="16.[151,376,1825,1885]" box="[151,279,1860,1885]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,272,1860,1885]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–10" captionStart-1="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId-0="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionStartId-1="18.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetBox-1="[162,1426,196,1884]" captionTargetId-0="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetId-1="figure-73@18.[161,1426,193,1888]" captionTargetPageId-0="15" captionTargetPageId-1="18" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." captionText-1="FIGURES 11–20. Phlaeothripinae genera. Antennae 11–18: (11) Akarethrips iotus; (12) Ecacanthothrips tibialis; (13) Eurhynchothrips messuicola; (14) Eugynothrips sumatranus; (15) Heliothripoides boltoni; (16) Isotrichothrips longirostris; (17) Litotetothrips sp.; (18) Phenicothrips daetymon. Head &amp; pronotum 19–20: (19) Asianthrips orientalis; (20) Apelaunothrips aokii." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918128" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4918128/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs 6–11</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1932,2029]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1436,151,573]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Small-sized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[292,468,1932,1957]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
with unusually short maxillary stylets; body surface weakly sculptured; head longer than wide, cheeks incut just behind eyes (
<figureCitation box="[651,725,1968,1993]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); eyes equally developed on dorsal and ventral surfaces, all ommatidia of equal size; postocular setae well-developed; stylets wide apart, V-shaped, not retracted anterior to postoccipital ridge (
<figureCitation box="[374,474,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 6, 8</figureCitation>
); antennae 8-segmented, VIII fused to VII but with weakly complete suture (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1421,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,196,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-73@18.[161,1426,193,1888]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Phlaeothripinae genera. Antennae 11–18: (11) Akarethrips iotus; (12) Ecacanthothrips tibialis; (13) Eurhynchothrips messuicola; (14) Eugynothrips sumatranus; (15) Heliothripoides boltoni; (16) Isotrichothrips longirostris; (17) Litotetothrips sp.; (18) Phenicothrips daetymon. Head &amp; pronotum 19–20: (19) Asianthrips orientalis; (20) Apelaunothrips aokii." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918128" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918128/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
), III with 3 slender sensoria, IV with 4, V and VI each with 2 similar sensoria; pronotum with 5 pairs of capitate setae, notopleural sutures complete; basantra present in male, weak in female; mesopresternum divided into three sclerites, median sclerite with pair of setae (
<figureCitation box="[654,723,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); sternopleural sutures absent; fore tarsal tooth present in both sexes; fore wings constricted medially, with duplicated cilia (
<figureCitation box="[862,933,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); pelta slightly hat-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1329,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); tergites II–VII with 2 pairs of wing-retaining setae; tergite IX with setae S1 and S2 of female expanded at apex; tube with straight sides, shorter than head; male tergite IX setae S2 short and stout (
<figureCitation box="[975,1058,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,185,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-87@15.[151,1436,185,1900]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Phlaeothripinae genera. (1) Ablemothrips maxillatus, antenna, head, pronotum &amp; fore leg; (2) Acanthothrips nodicornis, head &amp; fore leg; (3) Agynaikothrips sp., head; (4) Adraneothrips coloratus, head &amp; pronotum; (5) Androthrips ramachandrai, head, pronotum &amp; for legs. Akarethrips iotus 6–10: (6) Head, pronotum &amp; fore legs; (7) Forewing; (8) Basantra &amp; mesopresternum; (9) Metanotum &amp; Pelta; (10) Tergites VIII–IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918126" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918126/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), sternite VIII without pore plate. 
<typeStatus box="[151,207,404,428]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Dang &amp; Mound &amp; Qiao, 2014" authorityName="Dang &amp; Mound &amp; Qiao" authorityYear="2014" box="[309,501,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Akarethrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iotus" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[309,501,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Akarethrips iotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[508,561,404,427]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,439,464]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Comments</emphasis>
. This new genus shares character states of the fore wing and prosternum with genera of the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,306,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplothripini">Haplothripini</taxonomicName>
. Amongst the genera of that tribe in which species have three sensoria on the third segment (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K." pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="2919 - 2978" refId="ref62801" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K. (2007) Australian insects of the Haplothrips lineage (Thysanoptera - Phlaeothripinae). Journal of Natural History, 41 (45 - 48), 2919 - 2978. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930701783219" type="journal article" year="2007">Mound &amp; Minaei 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Minaei, K. &amp; Azemayeshfard, P. &amp; Mound, L. A." box="[337,544,511,536]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="55 - 64" refId="ref61942" refString="Minaei, K., Azemayeshfard, P. &amp; Mound, L. A. (2007) The southern Palaearctic genus Neoheegeria (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae): redefinition and key to species. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 150, 55 - 64. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 22119434 - 900000212" type="journal article" year="2007">
Minaei 
<emphasis box="[423,472,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
) it is distinguished by the exceptionally short maxillary stylets that are scarcely retracted into the head.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
